{{VG history|expandmenu=2}}

In the  [[history of video games]], the '''seventh generation''' primarily focuses on the consoles released since {{vgy|2005}} by [[Nintendo]], [[Microsoft]], and [[Sony]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sakazaki|first=Lloyd|url= http://seekingalpha.com/article/22075-seventh-generation-gaming-consoles-thinking-outside-the-box|title=Seventh Generation Gaming Consoles: Thinking Outside the Box|publisher=Seeking Alpha|date= 2006-12-11|accessdate=2008-06-08}}</ref>

For home consoles, the seventh generation began<ref>{{cite web | title=Seventh Generation Gaming Consoles: Thinking Outside the Box | url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/22075-seventh-generation-gaming-consoles-thinking-outside-the-box | accessdate=2009-01-12}}</ref> on November 22, 2005 with the release of Microsoft's [[Xbox 360]] and continued with the release of Sony's [[PlayStation 3]] on November 11, 2006, and Nintendo's [[Wii]] on November 19, 2006. Each new console introduced a new type of breakthrough technology. For example, the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 offered [[High-definition video|high-definition]] graphics, the Wii focused on integrating [[Wii Remote|controllers]] with [[Wii Remote#Sensing|movement sensors]] instead of using [[joystick]]s<ref>{{cite web|last=Wisniowski|first=Howard|url= http://www.analog.com/en/press-release/May_09_2006_ADI_Nintendo_Collaboration/press.html|title=Analog Devices And Nintendo Collaboration Drives Video Game Innovation With iMEMS Motion Signal Processing Technology|publisher=Analog Devices, Inc.|date= 2006-05-09|accessdate=2006-05-10}}</ref> (the PlayStation 3 also employs motion sensitivity, but to a lesser degree). Most of consoles have [[wireless]] controllers, while the Xbox 360 also has wired controllers as an alternative. The PlayStation 3 controller can be charged through the use of a USB-A/mini-b cable. The wireless Xbox 360 controller uses either a rechargeable battery pack or 2 AA batteries; the same can be said about the Wii.

For handheld consoles, the seventh generation began on November 21, 2004 with the North American introduction of the [[Nintendo DS]] as a "third pillar", alongside Nintendo's existing [[Game Boy Advance]] and [[Nintendo GameCube|GameCube]] consoles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.n-sider.com/contentview.php?contentid=515|title=Various Satoru Iwata comments regarding the Nintendo DS|author=Glen Bayer|publisher=N-sider.com|date=2004-03-01|accessdate=2007-10-04}}</ref> The Nintendo DS features a touch screen and built-in [[microphone]], and supports wireless [[IEEE 802.11]] ([[Wi-Fi]]) standards.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.darkain.com/nintendo_ds/nifi.php | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20050217195147/http://www.darkain.com/nintendo_ds/nifi.php | archivedate=2005-02-17 | title=Nintendo DS - WI-FI vs NI-FI | author=Darkain |date=2005-01-21 | accessdate=2006-04-02}}</ref> More recently, the new [[DSi]] features many new things including two built in cameras, the ability to download games from the DSi store, and a web browser. The [[PlayStation Portable]], released later the same year on December 12, 2004, followed a different pattern. It became the first handheld video game console to use an optical disc format, [[Universal Media Disc]] (UMD), as its primary storage media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamedaily.com/games/playstation-portable/psp/game-news/e3-2003-psp-press-release/4356/3143/| title=E3 2003: PSP Press Release| date=2003-12-31|publisher=gamedaily.com| accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us.playstation.com/Support/PSP/Movies/default.html| title=Support - PSP - Movies| publisher="Sony Computer Entertainment| accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref> Sony also gave the PlayStation Portable robust multi-media capability,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us.playstation.com/PSP/Features| title=PSP - About - Multimedia| publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment| accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref> connectivity with the PlayStation 3 and other PSPs, and [[Internet]] connectivity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manuals.playstation.net/document/en/ps3/current/remoteplay/remoteplay.html| title=User's Guide - Remote Play| publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment| accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us.playstation.com/Support/PSP/ConnectingToInternet/default.html| title=Support - PSP - Connecting to the Internet| publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment| accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref> The Nintendo DS likewise has connectivity to the internet through the [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]] and [[Nintendo DS Browser]], as well as wireless connectivity to other DS systems and Wii consoles. Despite high sales numbers for both consoles, PlayStation Portable sales have consistently lagged behind those of the Nintendo DS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gizmodo.com/gadgets/psp-vs-ds/8-reasons-why-the-psp-might-overtake-the-ds-327596.php| title=8 reasons why the PSP might overtake the DS| date=2007-11-29| publisher=Gizmodo| accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref>

{{TOClimit|limit=4}}

== Home consoles ==

=== Xbox 360 ===
{{main|Xbox 360}}

[[Microsoft]]'s Xbox 360 gained an early lead in terms of market share, largely due to its established [[Xbox Live]] online gaming system, and its early launch date which was one year before its rivals. Sales in North America and Europe have continued to be strong, even after the release of the [[Wii]] and [[PlayStation 3]]. Like its predecessor, the Xbox 360 received a muted reception in Japan,<ref>{{cite news|title=Muted hello for Xbox 360 in Japan|publisher=BBC|date=2005-12-10|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4517362.stm|accessdate=2007-10-28}}</ref> attributed to the lack of content aimed at Japanese gamers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fildes|first=Johnathan|title=Xbox still hopes to storm Japan|publisher=BBC|date=2006-09-23|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/5373066.stm|accessdate=2007-10-30}}</ref>

This early launch did come with some trouble, as [[Xbox 360 technical problems|technical problems]] appeared in a portion of Xbox 360 units sold. The most well known problem is the "[[Xbox 360 technical problems#Three flashing red lights|red ring of death]]", which received a great deal of attention due to some users' claims of having to replace their consoles multiple times. Microsoft addressed this by offering a three year warranty on all affected consoles and repairing them free of charge.<ref name="moneyback">{{cite web |title=Xbox 360 Warranty Coverage Expanded |publisher=Microsoft |date=2007-07-05 |url=http://support.xbox.com/support/en/us/xbox360/hardware/warranty/warrantyupdate/WarrantyUpdate.aspx |accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref> It also [[retroactive]]ly reimbursed owners of affected systems who paid for repairs.<ref name="moneyback"/> According to ''[[The Mercury News]]'', new models of the console featuring 65-nanometer technology will address this and other issues; the new technology is expected to reduce heat production, which will lower the risk of overheating and system failures; although, this has never been officially confirmed by Microsoft.<ref>{{cite web |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |title=Microsoft<U+2019>s next move? Code-name Falcon |publisher=[[The Mercury News]] |date=2007-07-09 |url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/aei/2007/07/09/microsofts_next_move_code-name_falcon/ |accessdate=2007-10-31}}</ref> There is also a new hardware error called E74. Similar to the RRoD, it's an error screen that appears on your 360. 

As they share many cross-platform games and compete for the same audience as their predecessors, frequent comparisons are made between the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3.<ref>{{cite web |date=2005-05-20 |last=Perry |first=Douglass |publisher=IGN |title=E3 2005: Microsoft's Xbox 360 vs. Sony's PlayStation 3 |url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/617/617951p1.html |accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref> The PS3 uses the [[Blu-ray]] format, while the Xbox 360 uses a standard [[DVD9]]. The Xbox 360 is less expensive to produce, and analysts expect that a mid-revision will allow Microsoft to break-even on manufacturing costs,<ref>{{cite web |date=2006-11-23 |last=Carless |first=Simon |publisher=Gamasutra |title=iSuppli: Xbox 360 Hardware Costs Now Profitable? |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=11833 |accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=2006-11-16 |publisher=iSuppli |title=PlayStation 3 Offers Supercomputer Performance at PC Pricing, iSuppli<U+2019>s Teardown Analysis Reveals |url=http://www.isuppli.com/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=17880 |accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref> while industry consensus is that the Xbox 360's conventional architecture is easier to develop for.<ref>{{cite web |date=2007-08-17 |last=Doerr |first=Nick |publisher=PS3 Fanboy |title=Ubisoft's GRAW team denies PS3 programming difficulty |url=http://playstation.joystiq.com/2007/08/17/ubisofts-graw-team-denies-ps3-programming-difficulty/and not a bad ass too
 |accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=2006-02-07 |last=Gualco |first=Scott |publisher=Gamer 2.0 |title=UPDATE PlayStation 3 Programming Predicament? |url=http://www.gamer20.com/platform/ps3/news/3521/ |accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref>

At the end of first half of 2007, the console stabilized at 11.6 million units shipped as sales dropped 60% while its rival, [[Wii]], gained momentum and [[Sony]] announced a competitive price drop on the [[PlayStation 3]].<ref>{{cite web |last=McDougall |first=Paul |title=Microsoft Xbox 360 Sales Plunge 60% As Problems Mount |publisher=[[InformationWeek]] |date=2007-07-20 | url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/personal_tech/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=201200157|accessdate=2007-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Lai |first=Marcus |title=Wii, Xbox 360 sales up; PS3 down at Ebay |publisher=Punch Jump |date=2007-08-30 |url=http://news.punchjump.com/blog/2007/08/30/wii-xbox-360-sales-up-ps3-down-at-ebay-2/ |accessdate=2007-11-22}}</ref>  Microsoft's strategy to boost sales with the release of the highly anticipated ''[[Halo 3]]'' in September 2007 paid off, outselling the Wii that month in North America.<ref name="Xbox36Wii">{{cite web |last=Boyer |first=Brandon |title=Halo 3 Drives Xbox 360 Sales Above Wii In September |publisher =Gamasutra |date=2007-10-19 |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=15918 |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> Microsoft's Entertainment and Devices Division experienced a huge increase in revenue, largely driven by the release of ''Halo 3'', and posted a quarterly profit for the first time in two years.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kuchera |first=Ben |title=Strong ''Halo 3'' launch helps Microsoft gaming to first profit in years |publisher=Ars Technica |date=2007-10-26 |url=http://arstechnica.com/gaming/news/2007/10/strong-halo-3-launch-helps-microsoft-to-first-ever-profit-on-gaming.ars |accessdate=2007-10-29}}</ref>

The Xbox 360's advantage over its competitors has been its quantity and quality of titles. The 2007 [[Game Critics Awards]] honoured the platform with 38 nominations and 11 wins <U+2013> more than any other platform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/nom-stats-2007.html |title=2007 Nominee Fast Facts |publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]] |accessdate=2008-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/win-stats-2007.html |title=2007 Winners Fast Facts |publisher=Game Critics Awards |accessdate=2008-06-25}}</ref> By March 2008, the Xbox 360 had reached a software [[attach rate]] of 7.5 games per console in the US <U+2013> a record for any console in history; the rate was 7.0 in Europe, while its competitors were 3.8 (PS3) and 3.5 (Wii), according to Microsoft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebitbag.com/2008/04/17/xbox-360-comes-in-2nd-for-march-sales/|title=Xbox 360 Comes In 2nd For March Sales |author=Torrence Davis |publisher=The Bitbag |date=2008-04-17 |accessdate=2008-06-25 |accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref> At the 2008 [[Game Developers Conference]], Microsoft announced that it expects over 1,000 games available for Xbox 360 by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thatvideogameblog.com/2008/02/20/microsoft-keynote-reveals-xbox-stats/|title=Microsoft keynote reveals Xbox stats |author=Rain Anderson |publisher=That VideoGame Blog |date=2008-02-20 |accessdate=2008-06-25}}</ref> The Xbox 360 has managed to gain a simultaneous release of titles which were initially planned to be PS3 exclusives, including ''[[Devil May Cry (series)|Devil May Cry]]'',<ref name="Devil May Cry">{{cite web |title=Official Press Release on DMC4 going Multiplatform |publisher=[[Capcom]] |date=2007-03-20 |url=http://ir.capcom.co.jp/english/news/html/e070320.html |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> ''[[Ace Combat]]'',<ref name="Ace Combat">{{cite web |url=http://www.namcobandaigames.com/news/press/press/199/page/1 |title=Namco Bandai Games announces the worldwide launch of Ace Combat 6: fires of liberation for the Xbox 360 |publisher=[[Namco Bandai]] |accessdate=2008-06-25}}</ref> ''[[Virtua Fighter (series)|Virtua Fighter]]'',<ref name="Virtua Fighter">{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |title=PS3 Loses Another Exclusive, Virtua Fighter 5 Comes to 360| publisher=Kotaku |date=2006-12-21 |url=http://kotaku.com/gaming/sega/ps3-loses-another-exclusive-virtua-fighter-5-comes-to-360-223566.php |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> ''[[Grand Theft Auto 4]]'',<ref name="Grand Theft Auto 4">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/action/grandtheftauto4/news.html?sid=6151640&mode=all |title=Grand Theft Auto IV Comes to Xbox 360 on Day One |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=2008-05-24}}</ref> ''[[Final Fantasy XIII]]'',<ref name="FFXIII360"/> and ''[[Tekken 6]]''.<ref name=tekken360/>

In August 2007, the first price drop was announced for all [[Stock Keeping Unit]]s (SKU's) of the Xbox 360.<ref name="lower price">{{cite web |title=Microsoft Lowers Xbox 360 Price |publisher=Xbox (Microsoft) |date=[[2007-08-06]] |url=http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/news/2007/0806-consoleprice.htm |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070820211136/http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/news/2007/0806-consoleprice.htm |archivedate=2007-08-20 |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> The Core system's price was reduced in the United States by $20, the Premium by $50, and the Elite model by $30.<ref name="lower price"/> Also, the [[HDMI]] out port, previously exclusive to the Elite system, was added to new models of the Premium and Core systems (and the new Arcade system).<ref>{{cite web |last=Bergfeld |first=Carlos |title=Microsoft Confirms HDMI Port on X360 Premium Model, Not Core |publisher=Shacknews |date=2007-08-08 |url=http://www.shacknews.com/onearticle.x/48351 |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref>

=== PlayStation 3 ===
{{main|PlayStation 3}}

[[Sony]]'s PlayStation 3 was released on November 11, 2006 in Japan and November 17, 2006 in USA and Canada. The system's reliance on new technology such as the [[Cell microprocessor]] and [[Blu-ray]] format has caused difficulties in manufacturing, especially the Blu-ray diode, leading to shortages at launch and the delay of the [[PAL region]] launches; however, by early December 2006, Sony announced that all production issues had been resolved.<ref>{{cite web| last =Graft| first =Kris| title =PS3 Manufacturing Troubles 'Solved'| publisher =Next Generation| date =[[2006-12-08]]| url =http://www.edge-online.com/news/sony-ps3-mfg-troubles-resolved| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref>

Market analysts<ref> {{cite web | title =Sony's other units depend on the PS3's success | publisher =CNN | date =[[2006-05-07]] | url =http://money.cnn.com/2006/05/07/technology/sony_reut0507/index.htm | archiveurl =http://www.webcitation.org/5fUxfqnva | archivedate=2009-03-23| accessdate =2007-12-18  }}</ref> and Sony executives have stated that the success of the PlayStation 3 and the [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] format are dependent on one another; Rich Marty, VP of New Business Development at [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]] stated that the <U+201C>PS3 is critical to the success of Blu-ray,"<ref>{{cite web | title =PS3 fuels Blu-ray revolution says Sony Pictures | publisher =PSPSPS | date =[[2007-09-06]] | url =http://www.pspsps.tv/2007/09/ps3_fuels_bluray_revolution_sa_1.html | accessdate =2007-12-18  }}</ref> while [[Phil Harrison]] stated that the PlayStation 3's success will be ensured because "the growth of the Blu-ray disc movie market ... is a positive factor which will play more into the consumer psyche ... as more consumer electronics firms launch standalone disc players, as more Blu-ray disc movies become available, and as more shelf space is dedicated to the category at retail."<ref>{{cite web | last =Gibson | first =Ellie | title =Blu-ray will help ensure success of PlayStation 3, says Harrison | publisher =[[GamesIndustry.biz]] | date =2007-03-13 | url =http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/blu-ray-will-help-ensure-ps3s-success-says-harrison | accessdate =2007-12-18  }}</ref>

Sony will provide support for its console with new titles from acclaimed first-party franchises such as ''[[Gran Turismo (series)|Gran Turismo]]'' and ''[[God of War (video game)|God of War]]'', and secured a number of highly anticipated third-party exclusive titles, including ''[[Metal Gear Solid 4: Guns of the Patriots|Metal Gear Solid 4]]'' and ''[[Final Fantasy Versus XIII]].'' Titles which were originally [[exclusive dealing|exclusive]] or recognised with the platform, such as ''[[Devil May Cry (series)|Devil May Cry]]'',<ref name="Devil May Cry"/> ''[[Ace Combat]]'',<ref name="Ace Combat"/> ''[[Virtua Fighter (series)|Virtua Fighter]]'',<ref name="Virtua Fighter"/> and ''[[Monster Hunter]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ir.capcom.co.jp/english/news/html/e071010.html |title=Capcom unleashes the beast as "Monster Hunter 3 (tri-)" rumbles its way onto the Nintendo Wii |publisher=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=2008-06-25}}</ref> have been released on other platforms. The previous ''[[Grand Theft Auto (series)|Grand Theft Auto]]'' titles were originally timed exclusives on the [[PlayStation 2]], before making their release on other platforms, such as the [[Xbox]], months later; however, ''[[Grand Theft Auto 4]]'', the latest installment, arrived day one on the Xbox 360 with the release of the PlayStation 3 version, as well as having exclusive content for the Xbox 360.<ref name="Grand Theft Auto 4"/> Announced exclusives titles for the PlayStation 3 such as ''[[Assassin's Creed]]'';<ref>{{cite web| last =Hatfield| first =Daemon| title =Assassin's Creed Loses PS3 Exclusivity| publisher =IGN| date =[[2006-08-30]]| url =http://au.ps3.ign.com/articles/729/729420p1.html| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref> ''[[Bladestorm: The Hundred Years' War]]'' and ''[[Fatal Inertia]]'' were released on Xbox 360 as well, with the latter making its release on Xbox 360 before the PlayStation 3 version.<ref>{{cite web | last =Boyes | first =Emma | title =More PS3 exclusives head to 360  | publisher =[[GameSpot]] | date =[[2006-11-22]] | url =http://www.gamespot.com/news/6162235.html | accessdate =2007-12-18  }}</ref> The ''Katamari'' series, which has long been PlayStation 2 exclusives, found the latest installment, ''[[Beautiful Katamari]]'', exclusive to Xbox 360.<ref>{{cite web | last =Kohler | first =Chris | title =Sony's Lost Exclusives: A Timeline | publisher =''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' | date =[[2007-07-02]] | url =http://blog.wired.com/games/2007/07/sonys-lost-excl.html | accessdate =2007-12-18  }}</ref> These releases have fueled rumors and fear that ''[[Final Fantasy XIII]]'' and ''[[Tekken 6]]'', two highly anticipated exclusive PlayStation 3 games at the time, would also be available for Xbox 360, the PlayStation 3's primary competitor.<ref>{{cite web| last =Robischon| first =Noah| title =Metal Gear Solid 4 Is PS3 Exclusive - Last In Series| publisher =Kotaku| date =[[2007-07-11]]| url =http://kotaku.com/gaming/e307/metal-gear-solid-4-is-ps3-exclusive-+-last-in-series-277361.php| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Jackson | first =Mike | title =PS3 could lose FFXIII as an exclusive | publisher =[[ComputerAndVideoGames.com|CVG]] | date =[[2007-03-22]] | url =http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=160471 | accessdate = 2007-12-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Smith | first= Luke | title= Tekken 6 bound for Xbox 360? | url = http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3156143 | publisher= [[1UP.com]] | date= 2007-01-02| accessdate=2008-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebitbag.com/2007/10/16/tekken-6-on-xbox-360-is-highly-probable/|title= The Bitbag &raquo; Tekken 6 On Xbox 360 Is Highly Probable|publisher=TheBitBag|accessdate=2008-06-01|accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=153152 |title=Tekken 6 touted for Xbox 360|publisher=[[Computer and Video Games]]|accessdate=2008-06-01}}</ref> At E3 2008, it was announced that ''Final Fantasy XIII'' would be simultaneously released on the Xbox 360 in Europe and North America;<ref name="FFXIII360">{{cite web|url=http://g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/tag/36/Videogames.html#687020|title=Final Fantasy XIII Comes to the 360|coauthors=G4 tv|publisher=X-Play|language=English|accessdate=2008-07-14}}</ref> later on October 8, 2008, it was announced that ''Tekken 6'' would also be releasing on the Xbox 360;<ref name=tekken360>[http://www.gamespot.com/news/6198775.html?sid=6198775 TGS 2008: Tekken 6 smacking Xbox 360 - News at GameSpot<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.joystiq.com/2008/10/08/microsoft-confirms-tekken-6-for-360-fall-2009-release/ Microsoft confirms Tekken 6 for 360, fall 2009<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> however, ''Metal Gear Solid 4'' and ''Final Fantasy Versus XIII'' still remain PlayStation 3 exclusives.<ref>[http://thelonegamer.wordpress.com/2007/12/02/ten-coolest-things-about-tekken-6/ Ten Coolest Things About Tekken 6 <U+00AB> The Lone Gamer<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://kotaku.com/340097/mgs4-360-rumor-smashed-yet-again Rumor Smash: MGS4 360 Rumor Smashed Yet Again<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://ps3.thegamereviews.com/story-342-Rumor-Killer-No-MGS4-on-360-says-Konami.html Rumor Killer: No MGS4 on 360, says Konami - PS3 News from The Game Reviews<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://gamer.blorge.com/2008/03/03/xbox-360-will-never-get-metal-gear-solid-4-due-to-size/ Xbox 360 will never get Metal Gear Solid 4 due to size - GAMER.BLORGE<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://kotaku.com/5044645/kingdom-hearts-a-ps3-exclusive-will-be-seen-at-tgs Rumor: Kingdom Hearts A PS3 Exclusive, Will Be Seen At TGS<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Sony has blamed lower-than-expected sales, loss of exclusive titles in the PlayStation 3 software library, its higher price, and stock shortages.<ref>{{cite web | last =Kalning | first =Kristin | title =Sony aims for comeback win with PS3 | publisher =[[MSNBC]] | date =[[2007-12-02]] | url =http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/22044630/ | accessdate = 2007-12-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Ivan | first =Tom | title =Hirai: Sony's Focus Is Now On PS3 Software | publisher = [[Next Generation Magazine|Next Generation]] | date =[[2007-12-16]] | url =http://www.edge-online.com/news/hirai-sonys-focus-is-now-on-ps3-software | accessdate = 2007-12-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Brightman | first =James | title =Interview: Jack Tretton Reflects on Year One as SCEA Chief | publisher =GameDaily | date =[[2007-12-07]] | url =http://www.gamedaily.com/games/uncharted-drakes-fortune/playstation-3/game-features/interview-jack-tretton-reflects-on-year-one-as-scea-chief/6185/71250/?biz=1 | accessdate = 2007-12-18 }}</ref>

In July 2007, [[Sony]] announced a drop in the price of the console by $100.<ref>{{cite web| last =Hillis| first =Scott| title =Sony cuts price on Playstation 3 by $100| publisher =Reuters| date =[[2007-07-09]]| url =http://www.reuters.com/article/technologyNews/idUSN0726030420070709| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref> This measure only applied to the 60 GB models and was exclusive to the United States and Canada, where those models are no longer in production.<ref>{{cite web| last =Thorsen| first =Tor| title =60GB PS3 'no longer in production'| publisher =GameSpot AU| date =[[2007-07-13]]| url =http://au.gamespot.com/news/6175011.html| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref>

On October 18, 2007, Sony announced a $100 price drop for the 80 GB model and a new $399 40 GB model to launch on November 2, 2007<ref>{{cite news| title =Sony Press Release| url=http://www.us.playstation.com/News/PressReleases/429| date =[[2007-11-23]]| publisher =[[Sony]]| accessdate=2007-12-02}}</ref> with reduced features such as the removal of backward compatibility with [[Playstation 2|PS2]] games. Within weeks, Sony announced that sales of the 40 GB and 80 GB models by major retailers had increased 192%.<ref>{{cite news| last = Williams | first =Martyn | title =PS3 sales jump in US on heels of price cut | publisher =Washington Post | date =[[2007-11-23]] | url =http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/23/AR2007112300645.html | accessdate = 2007-11-25 }}</ref>

In November 2008, Sony launched a $499 160 GB model.<ref>{{cite news| title =GC 08| url=http://playstation.joystiq.com/2008/08/20/160gb-model-also-announced-for-america-499-november-release/| date=2008-08-20| publisher =[[PS3fanboy]]| accessdate=2008-08-20}}</ref>

=== Wii ===
{{main|Wii}}

[[Nintendo]] entered this generation with a new approach embodied by its Wii console. The company planned to attract current hard-core and casual gamers,<ref>{{cite news | last =Morris | first =Chris  | title =Nintendo continues to play coy | publisher = CNN | date =[[2006-05-09]] | url =http://money.cnn.com/2006/05/09/technology/e3_nintendo/index.htm | archiveurl =http://www.webcitation.org/5fV21iwH5 | archivedate=2009-03-23 | accessdate =2007-12-12}}</ref> non-gamers,<ref>{{cite news | last =Hermida | first =Alfred  | title =Nintendo shows new games console | publisher = BBC News | date =[[2006-05-10]] | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/4756625.stm | accessdate =2007-12-12}}</ref> and lapsed gamers by focusing on new gameplay experiences and new forms of interaction with games rather than cutting edge graphics and expensive technology.<ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite news | last =Hartley | first =Matt  | title =Reginald Fils-Aime: Nintendo goes for wild ride | publisher = [[The Globe and Mail]] | date =2007-12-10 | url =http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20071210.wdecisionPOINT1208/BNStory/Technology/home | accessdate =2007-12-12}}</ref> This approach was previously implemented in the [[Handheld game console|portable]] market with the [[Nintendo DS]].<ref name="money"/> Nintendo expressed hope that the new control schemes it has implemented will render current conventionally controlled consoles obsolete, leading to Nintendo capturing a large portion of the existing market as well.<ref name="Iwata Speech 06">{{cite web | url=http://www.nintendo.co.jp/n10/e3_2006/speech/english.html | publisher=Nintendo | title=Nintendo President, Satoru Iwata, media briefing speech at E3 2006 | accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref>

This strategy paid off, with demand for the Wii outstripping supply throughout 2007.<ref>{{cite web| last =Yen| first =Yi-Wyn| title =Wii woes for the wee ones on Xmas| publisher =CNN| date =[[2007-10-05]]| url =http://money.cnn.com/2007/10/03/technology/nintendo_wii.fortune/?postversion=2007100417| archiveurl =http://www.webcitation.org/5fV29rA2s| archivedate=2009-03-23| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref> Since Nintendo profited on each console right from the start unlike its competitors,<ref>{{cite web| last =Ehrenberg| first =Ron| title =Game Console Wars II: Nintendo Shaves Off Profits, Leaving Competition Scruffy| publisher =Seeking Alpha| date =[[2007-05-03]]| url =http://seekingalpha.com/article/34357-game-console-wars-ii-nintendo-shaves-off-profits-leaving-competition-scruffy| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref> it has already achieved very positive returns.<ref>{{cite web| title =Nintendo jumps ahead of Sony in market value| publisher =[[The Age]]| date =[[2007-06-25]]| url =http://www.theage.com.au/news/Technology/Nintendo-jumps-ahead-of-Sony-in-market-value/2007/06/25/1182623808686.html| accessdate =2007-10-25}}</ref> With only a few exceptions, monthly worldwide sales for the Wii have been higher than the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3,<ref name="Xbox36Wii"/><ref name="regain">{{cite news  | last =Levine | first =Barry | title =Gamers Buy 350,000 Wii Consoles in Single Week | publisher =CIO Today | date =[[2007-11-28]] | url =http://www.cio-today.com/news/Wii-Sells-350-000-Units-in-Single-Week/story.xhtml?story_id=13000G0B8RMG| accessdate =2007-12-12}}</ref><ref name="PS3leads">{{cite news  | last =Takenaka | first =Kiyoshi| title =Sony PS3 tops Nintendo Wii in Japan for first time | publisher =[[Forbes]]| date =[[2007-11-30]] | url =http://in.reuters.com/article/technologyNews/idINIndia-30766820071130 | accessdate =2007-12-12}}</ref> eroding Microsoft's early lead and widening the gap between its [[market share]] and Sony's.<ref name="money">{{cite web| title =The untold story of how the Wii beat the Xbox 360, PlayStation 3| publisher =CNNMoney| date =[[2007-04-25]]| url =http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2007/05/01/8405654/?postversion=2007042509| archiveurl =http://www.webcitation.org/5fV2IXcTP| archivedate=2009-03-23| accessdate =2007-05-01}}</ref> On September 12, 2007, it was reported by the British newspaper ''[[Financial Times]]'' that the Wii's sales had surpassed the Xbox 360, which was released one year previously, and became the market leader in worldwide home console sales for the current generation.<ref name="wiileads">{{cite web | last =Sanchanta| first =Mariko|title= Nintendo<U+2019>s Wii takes console lead| publisher =Financial Times| date=[[2007-09-12]]|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/51df0c84-6154-11dc-bf25-0000779fd2ac.html|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5fV2Od1Rb|archivedate=2009-03-23|accessdate=2007-09-12}}</ref>

As in previous generations, Nintendo has provided strong support for its new console with popular first-party franchises like ''[[Mario (series)|Mario]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda (series)|The Legend of Zelda]]'', ''[[Metroid (series)|Metroid]]'', and ''[[Pok<U+00E9>mon (video games)|Pok<U+00E9>mon]]'', among others. To appeal to casual and non-gamers, Nintendo has also created the ''[[Wii Series]]'' of games, where players make use of the motion-sensing abilities of the console and its peripherals to simulate real world activities, such as sports, table games, music, or doing exercises.<ref>{{cite web | title = Wii Sports Part 1: A Truly Ground-breaking Collection of Games | publisher = [[Nintendo]] | url =http://wiiportal.nintendo-europe.com/135.html | accessdate =2007-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Wii Sports Part 4: Games That Even the People Watching Can Enjoy | publisher = [[Nintendo]] | url =http://wiiportal.nintendo-europe.com/142.html | accessdate =2007-12-12}}</ref>

Publishers such as [[Ubisoft]], [[EA]], [[Capcom]], and [[Majesco Entertainment|Majesco]] continue to release exclusive titles for the console, but the Wii's strongest titles still remain within its first-party line-up. Analysts speculated that this will change in time as the Wii's growing popularity persuades third-party publishers to focus on it;<ref name="regain"/><ref>{{cite news | last =Wingfield | first =Nick | coauthors =Iwatani Kane, Yukari  | title =Wii and DS Turn Also-Ran Nintendo Into Winner in Videogames Business | publisher =Wall Street Journal | date =[[2007-04-19]] | url =http://online.wsj.com/public/article/SB117691936534774315-0q7Hxbw4nJnlZXw0F_ZCD6Dx5MI_20080418.html?mod=blogs | accessdate = 2007-12-12 }}</ref> however, some third party developers are beginning to express frustration at low software sales. [[Goichi Suda]], developer of ''[[No More Heroes (video game)|No More Heroes]]'' for the Wii, noted that "only Nintendo titles are doing well. This isn't just because of the current situation in Japan, as this is happening outside Japan. I am very surprised about the reality about Wii, because before I was making this game, I wasn't expecting that Wii would be a console targeted only for non-gamers. I expected more games for hardcore gamers. The reality is different to what I expected."<ref>{{cite web| last= Hicks | first= Chris | title=Suda 51: Third party Wii games aren<U+2019>t selling |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=179648 | publisher=[[Computer and Video Games|CVG]]| date= [[2008-01-16]] | accessdate= 2008-01-25}}</ref> Conversely, the PAL publisher of ''No More Heroes'' [[Rising Star Games]] were greatly impressed with the games sales.<ref>[http://www.mcvuk.com/news/29950/Rising-Star-enjoys-Wii-chart-success Rising Star enjoys Wii chart success - www.mcvuk.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Goichi Suda later retracted his comment, saying his "point was that ''No More Heroes'', unlike a lot of Nintendo Wii titles currently available is the kind of product which will attract a different kind of consumer to the hardware, ''i.e.'' gamers who are looking for a different genre to the products which have been successful on this platform thus far."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grasshopper.co.jp/ |title=Suda 51: Retracted Comment  |accessdate=2008-01-21 |date=2008-01-20 |publisher=Grasshopper Manufacture}}</ref>

In early 2008, the [[NPD Group]] revealed sales data showing that, while the Wii's life-to-date [[attach rate]] is low, in December 2007, it reached 8.11<U+2014>higher than the attach rates for the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 in that month.<ref>{{cite web |last=Casamassina |first= Matt | title= Wii Tie Ratio at 8:1 in December | url= http://wii.ign.com/articles/847/847472p1.html | publisher= IGN | date= [[2008-01-24]]| accessdate=2008-01-25}}</ref> The Wii's low overall attach rate could be explained by reference to its rapidly increasing [[installed base]], as financial analysts have pointed to the Xbox 360's high attach rates as indicative of an unhealthy lack of installed base growth, and warned that what actually benefits third-party developers is <U+201C>quicker adoption of hardware and a rapidly growing installed base on which to sell progressively more game units,<U+201D> which tends to lower the attach rate of a product.<ref>{{cite web |last= Dobson |first= Jason | title = Opinion: Xbox 360 Software Attach Rate Is 'Alarming' | url= http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=11796 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] | date= [[2006-11-21]]| accessdate=2008-01-25}}</ref>

