==== Discontinuations and revisions ====

* The PlayStation 3 20 GB was discontinued in North America in April, 2007<ref>{{cite web |last=Thorsen |first=Tor |coauthors=Emma Boyes |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6168876.html |title=20 GB PS3 officially discontinued in North America |publisher=GameSpot |date=[[2007-04-11]] |accessdate=2007-04-15}}</ref> and effectively discontinued in Japan in early 2008.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boyes |first=Emma |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6184539.html |title=Sony discontinuing 20GB and 60GB PS3 in Japan |publisher=GameSpot |date=[[2008-01-10]] |accessdate=2008-01-10}}</ref>
* The PlayStation 3 60 GB was discontinued in [[NTSC]] territories by September 2007, and replaced with the 80 GB version.<ref>{{cite web |last=Thorsen |first=Tor |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6175011.html |title=E3 07: Hirai: 60GB PS3 'no longer in production' |publisher=GameSpot |date=[[2007-07-13]] |accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref>
* The PlayStation 3 60 GB was effectively discontinued for [[PAL]] territories in late 2007. When the remaining stock in stores was sold, the 40 GB version served as its replacement.
* Sony announced before the PS3 launch in Europe that the PlayStation 2's [[Emotion Engine]] CPU would be removed from it for cost savings, and all backwards compatibility would be software-based.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boxer |first=Steve |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2007/mar/01/sonyplaystation.sony |title=PlayStation 3 loses all Emotion in Europe |publisher=Guardian |date=[[2007-03-01]] |accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref> This is also the same for the 80 GB model launched in the North American market in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last=Androvich |first=Mark |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/new-80gb-ps3-eliminates-emotion-engine-chip |title=New 80GB PS3 eliminates "emotion engine" chip |publisher=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |date=[[2007-07-09]] |accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref>
* An HDMI out port was added to the Premium Xbox 360 in August 2007.<ref> {{cite web| last =Callaham| first =John| title =HDMI Port In Xbox 360 Premium System Confirmed; Game Included?| publisher =FiringSquad| date =[[2007-08-08]]| url =http://www.firingsquad.com/news/newsarticle.asp?searchid=16873| accessdate =2007-10-30}}</ref>
* The Xbox 360 Core system was discontinued and replaced by the "Arcade" version in October, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cohen |first=Peter |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/138764/xbox_360_arcade_officially_debuts.html |title=Xbox 360 Arcade Officially Debuts |publisher=''[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]'' |date=[[2007-10-23]] |accessdate=2007-10-29}}</ref>
* The price of the Xbox 360 Premium version was dropped to $299 in North America on July 13, 2008. Supplies of the existing 20 GB model were exhausted by early August and it was replaced by an identical model with a 60&nbsp;GB [[HDD]] at a [[MSRP]] of $349.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/AheadoftheCurve/wireStory?id=5365862| title=Microsoft cuts Xbox price by $50, plans 60GB model| date=2008-07-13| agency=Associated Press| accessdate=2008-07-13}}</ref>
* The Playstation 3 40 GB was discontinued in all territories in early August 2008 and the new 80 GB version served as its replacement.
* The [[Xbox 360]] Arcade 256MB internal memory SKU was discontinued in all territories in early 2009 and a new 512MB internal memory SKU still named the [[Xbox 360]] Arcade was reliesed.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.xbox360.ign.com/articles/996/996206p1.html| title=Microsoft increases the internal memory of the [[Xbox 360]] Arcade to 512MB| date=2009-06-18| agency=IGN| accessdate=2009-06-18}}</ref>

==== Backward compatibility ====

The [[Wii]] and the original two models of the [[PlayStation 3]] are fully [[Backward compatibility|backwards compatible]] with titles from their previous counterparts and the Wii also offers support for some of [[Nintendo GameCube|its predecessor's]] accessories. Later versions of the PlayStation 3 and all models of the [[Xbox 360]] only offer partial support and use [[software emulation]] for backwards compatibility. Current versions of the PS3 do not offer [[PlayStation 2]] compatibility at all, though [[PlayStation|PS1]] compatibility is retained. The Xbox 360's compatibility is increased through game-specific [[Patch (computing)|patches]] automatically downloaded from Xbox Live or downloaded and burned to a CD or DVD from the Xbox website<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xbox.com/en-US/games/backwardcompatibilitygameslist.htm|publisher=Xbox.com |title=Xbox 360 - Original Xbox Games on Xbox 360<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=2008-05-13}}</ref> and the PS3's compatibility is expanded with firmware updates. All three consoles provide titles from older consoles for download; the Xbox 360 through the [[List of Xbox Originals|Xbox Originals]] service, the PlayStation 3 through the [[PlayStation Store]], and the Wii through the [[Virtual Console]]. When purchased, the game requested is then saved to the console's internal memory.

==== High definition and enhanced definition video ====

Both the [[PlayStation 3]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us.playstation.com/Support/PS3/GettingStarted/default.html|title=Setting Up the PLAYSTATION3|publisher=SCEA|author=SCEA|accessdate=2008-06-30}}</ref> and the [[Xbox 360]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/gaming/xbox-360/shane-kim-talks-360-1080p-game-output-201816.php|title=Shane Kim Talks 360 1080p Game Output|publisher=Kotaku|author=Brian Crecente|date=2006-09-20|accessdate=2008-06-30}}</ref> support [[1080p]] [[high definition video]] output. However, the output signal may be protected by [[digital rights management]] and may require an [[High-bandwidth Digital Content Protection|HDCP]]-compliant display if [[HDMI]] is used. The [[Xbox Live Marketplace]] service and the United States' [[PlayStation Store]] offer HD movies, TV shows, movie trailers and clips for download to the console's HDD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/events/e32007/articles/disneystudiosnowonmarketplace.htm|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070713223845/http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/events/e32007/articles/disneystudiosnowonmarketplace.htm|archivedate=2007-07-13|title=Walt Disney Studios now on XBox Marketpalce|publisher=Xbox.com|accessdate=2008-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us.playstation.com/News/PressReleases/480| title=PLAYSTATIONNetwork's Video Delivery Service to Offer Movies and TV Shows for Purchase and TV Shows for Purchase and Rental Through PLAYSTATION3 and PSP (PlayStationPortable)| date=2008-07-15| publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment America| accessdate=2008-10-06}}</ref> Other PlayStation Stores only feature movie trailers and clips for video download.

While only a small number of games [[Rendering (computer graphics)|render]] the video output in full 1080p, all games can be automatically scaled to this resolution.

The Wii is capable of outputting 480p for the Wii Menu and most games through a component cable which must be purchased separately.

== Handheld systems ==
{{seealso|Comparison of handheld game consoles}}



For [[handheld game console|video game handhelds]], the seventh generation began with the release of the [[Nintendo DS]] on November 21, 2004. This handheld was based on a design fundamentally different from the [[Game Boy]] and other handheld video game systems. The Nintendo DS offered new modes of input over previous generations such as a touch screen, the ability to connect wirelessly using IEE 802.11b, as well as a microphone to speak to in-game NPCs.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.darkain.com/nintendo_ds/nifi.php | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20050217195147/http://www.darkain.com/nintendo_ds/nifi.php | archivedate=2005-02-17 | title=Nintendo DS - WI-FI vs NI-FI | author=Darkain |date=2005-01-21 | accessdate=2008-05-17}}</ref> On December 12, 2004, Sony released its first handheld, [[PlayStation Portable]]. The PlayStation Portable was marketed at launch to an above 25 year old<ref>{{cite web  |last=Brightman |first=James |title=SCEA: PSP Will Be Big Revenue Driver |publisher=GameDaily |date=2007-06-26 |url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/features/scea-psp-will-be-big-revenue-driver/70598/ |accessdate=2007-11-05 }}</ref> or "core gamer" market,<ref>{{cite web |last=Sheffield |first=Brandon |title=What's the Dille? Sony's Marketing Head Gets Heated |publisher=Gamasutra |date=2007-07-24  |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/1534/whats_the_dille_sonys_marketing_.php?page=4 |accessdate=2007-11-05 }}</ref> while the Nintendo DS proved to be popular with both core gamers and new customers.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rojas |first=Peter |title=The Engadget Interview: Reggie Fils-Aime, Executive Vice President of Sales and Marketing for Nintendo |publisher=Engadget |date=2006-02-20 |url=http://www.engadget.com/2006/02/20/the-engadget-interview-reggie-fils-aime-executive-vice-preside/  |accessdate =2007-11-05}}</ref>

[[Nokia Corporation]] plans to revive its [[N-Gage]] platform in the form of a service for selected [[S60 platform|S60]] devices. [[N-Gage 2.0|This new service]] launched on April 3, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.n-gage.com/ngi/ngage/web/g0/en/community/articles.Detail.general-anewdayforngage.1.html |title= A New Day for N-Gage |publisher=Nokia |accessdate=2008-04-03}}</ref>

Other less-popular handheld systems released during this generation include the [[Gizmondo]] (launched on 19 March 2005 and discontinued in February 2006) and the [[GP2X]] (launched on 10 November 2005 and discontinued in August 2008). The [[GP2X Wiz]], [[Pandora (console)|Pandora]] and [[Gizmondo 2]] are due to be released in 2009.

Another aspect of the seventh generation was the beginning of direct competition between dedicated handheld gaming devices, and increasingly powerful pda/cellphone devices such as the [[iPhone]] and various devices powered by [[Windows Mobile]].  Simple games such as tetris and solitare had existed for PDA devices since their introduction, but by 2009 PDAs and phones had grown sufficiently powerful to where complex graphical games could be implemented, with the advantage of distribution over wireless broadband.

